(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 8 :title "Chapter 8 — Continuations" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/08-continuations.md" :size 2798 :sha256 "a89dcb343331346b" :content "---\nslug: sakura-scheme-book-reference-08\ntitle: Continuations\nbook: reference\nchapter: 8\nof: 16\npart: I\napp: scheme-repl\npalette: book-standard\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane Q9)\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-10\nprev: 07-streams\nnext: 09-environments\n---\n\n# Chapter 8 — Continuations\n\nA continuation is *what to do next*, made into a first-class value you can save and call later. This chapter is a light tour.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> The rest-of-the-program is usually invisible. Continuations make it visible — you can grab it, hold onto it, call it again. That's why they're strange the first time you see them.\n\n## call/cc\n\n```scheme\n(define (test-cc)\n  (+ 1 (call/cc (lambda (k) (+ 2 3)))))\n\n(display (test-cc)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n6\n```\n\n`call/cc` calls a function with the current continuation. If the function returns normally, the continuation isn't used. Here 1 + (2 + 3) = 6.\n\n## Escaping with a continuation\n\n```scheme\n(define (find-first-even lst)\n  (call/cc\n    (lambda (return)\n      (for-each (lambda (x) (if (even? x) (return x))) lst)\n      #f)))\n\n(display (find-first-even '(1 3 5 4 7))) (newline)\n(display (find-first-even '(1 3 5 7))) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n4\n#f\n```\n\nThe continuation `return` exits the loop immediately when an even number is found.\n\n## Saving a continuation\n\nContinuations can be saved and called later.\n\n```scheme\n(define saved-cont #f)\n\n(define (save-and-continue)\n  (+ 1 (call/cc (lambda (k)\n                   (set! saved-cont k)\n                   10))))\n\n(display (save-and-continue)) (newline)\n;; Later: (saved-cont 20) would produce 21 — but calling it in this\n;; document would need the runtime, so we describe the shape.\n(display '(if-we-called-saved-cont-with-20-we-would-get-21)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n11\n(if-we-called-saved-cont-with-20-we-would-get-21)\n```\n\n## When to use them\n\n```scheme\n(define continuation-uses\n  '(early-escape\n    coroutines\n    backtracking-search\n    exception-handling\n    non-local-return))\n\n(for-each (lambda (u) (display u) (newline)) continuation-uses)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\nearly-escape\ncoroutines\nbacktracking-search\nexception-handling\nnon-local-return\n```\n\n## What you know now\n\n- Continuations = *rest of the program* as a first-class value.\n- `call/cc` grabs the current continuation.\n- Early-escape is the most common use.\n- Saved continuations can be called later for backtracking or coroutines.\n\n## Try before you turn the page\n\n```scheme\n(display (call/cc (lambda (k) 42))) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n42\n```\n\nIf you can escape a loop with a continuation, you're ready for environments.\n\n---\n\nCross-references:\n\n- [[book-of-reference#chapter-3]] — tail-recursion.\n- [[book-of-reference#chapter-6]] — metacircular.\n- [[book-of-reference#chapter-9]] — environments.\n")
